<div class="container-fluid">
    <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-1 d-xlg-none"></div>
    <div class="col-sm-3 justify-content-end mt-5 tipCol">
        <div class="tips">
        <p class="mb-5">
            <h5><i class="far fa-lightbulb cyan-text"></i> &nbsp;Tip #1:</h5> The <strong>Greatest Common Factor</strong> is the largest number by which both the <strong>numerator</strong> and <strong>denominator</strong> can be divided. If you know the greatest common factor between two numbers, divide each by that number to get the <strong>simplified</strong> (also known as the <strong>reduced</strong>) fraction.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-5">
            <h5><i class="far fa-lightbulb cyan-text"></i> &nbsp;Tip #2:</h5> Just because the numerator and/or denominator are large numbers does <em>not</em> mean the fraction must be reduced.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-5">
            <h5><i class="far fa-lightbulb cyan-text"></i> &nbsp;Tip #3:</h5> Recall from the previous level that if the <strong>numerator</strong> (in this case, the number on the <em>left</em>) is greater than the <strong>denominator</strong> (the number on the <em>right</em>), then you know there is at least 1 whole number in the answer. 
        </p>
        <p class="mb-5">
            <h5><i class="far fa-lightbulb cyan-text"></i> &nbsp;Tip #4:</h5> If the numerator is larger than the denominator, use the following tip: after dividing the <strong>numerator</strong> by the <strong>denominator</strong>, write the whole number as the first part of your answer. If there is a <strong>remainder</strong>, then the remainder will become the numerator of the fraction portion (the second part) of the answer. (Note: But be sure to simplify the fraction portion of your answer, if possible!).
        </p>
        <p class="mb-5">
            <h5><i class="far fa-lightbulb cyan-text"></i> &nbsp;Tip #5:</h5> If the <strong>denominator</strong> is <strong>divisible</strong> by the <strong>numerator</strong>, then you know you will need to <strong>reduce</strong> or <strong>simplify</strong> the fraction. Learn more <a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisibility_rule">here</a> about the <strong>Divisibility rule</strong>.
        </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-6">
            <h4 class="text-center instructions mt-4">Answer each with a reduced fraction. Tap the card to see the solution.</h4>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                @foreach(var item in Model){
                    <div class="cardContainer">
                        <div class="flashCard" >
                            <div class="front">
                                <p>@item.Dividend</p>
                                <p class="mx-3" style="font-size:42px">รท</p>
                                <p>@item.Divisor</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="back mb-5">@item.Whole
                                <span class="fraction">
                                    @item.Answer
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            @* <div style="font-size:16px" class="back my-5">Decimal: 1.333</div> *@
                        </div>
                    </div>
                }
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
